Four hundred and seventy one Covid-19 patients were hospitalised on Tuesday. Another 1,471 were under the home-based care programme as per the data from the Health ministry. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe, in a statement, confirmed that 153 more people had tested positive for the virus from a sample of 3,922 tested within 24 hours. The new cases comprised 123 Kenyans and 30 foreign nationals aged between one and 80 years. “Fortunately, today there are no reported deaths and therefore our cumulative fatalities remain at 1,766,” Kagwe said. Within the 24 hours, 54 patients recovered from the disease, 35 from the home-based isolation and care programme and the remaining discharged from hospitals. This pushed the total recoveries to 83,990. “Twenty seven patients are in the Intensive Care Unit, 12 of whom are on ventilator support and 15 on supplemental oxygen,” the CS said. “Another 16 patients are separately on supplemental oxygen, with 12 of them in the general wards and four in the high dependency unit.” Ninety three of the new cases were from Nairobi. Mombasa came second after registering 13 more cases. Kiambu recorded eight, Nakuru six and Turkana five. Kajiado, Kisumu and Taita Taveta counties had three cases each. Busia, Nandi, Trans Nzoia, Uasin Gishu and Kirinyaga had two cases each while Elgeyo Marakwet, Embu, Kilifi, Machakos, Makueni, Meru, Murang’a, Samburu and Siaya had one each. Nairobi’s Dagoretti North had 19 cases, Lang’ata 14 and Kibra 12. Embakasi Central, Kasarani, Ruaraka and Westlands recorded six cases each; while Embakasi West had five. Other subcounties that recorded new cases included Mathare and Makadara with four each; Dagoretti South, Embakasi North, Kamukunji and Starehe with two each; and Embakasi East, Embakasi South and Roysambu that had one each.